We first extract the key numbers from the end-of-period amounts of the balance sheet and cash flow statement.

Step 1. Calculate the Current Ratio:
 • Total Current Assets = 29,413,723.95
 • Total Current Liabilities = 8,028,630.43  
 Current Ratio = 29,413,723.95 / 8,028,630.43 ≈ 3.66

Step 2. Calculate the Quick Ratio:
 • Quick Assets = Current Assets – Inventory = 29,413,723.95 – 7,400,000.00 = 22,013,723.95  
 • Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Current Liabilities = 22,013,723.95 / 8,028,630.43 ≈ 2.74

Step 3. Calculate the Debt to Asset Ratio:
 • Total Liabilities (the sum of Accounts Payable and Taxes Payable) = 8,028,630.43  
 • Total Assets = 39,772,748.32  
 Debt to Asset Ratio = 8,028,630.43 / 39,772,748.32 ≈ 0.20

Step 4. Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio:
 • Total Owner’s Equity = 31,744,117.89  
 Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity = 8,028,630.43 / 31,744,117.89 ≈ 0.25

Step 5. Calculate the Cash Flow to Debt Ratio:
 • Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = -10,442,735.47  
 • Total Debt is taken as Total Liabilities = 8,028,630.43  
 Cash Flow to Debt Ratio = -10,442,735.47 / 8,028,630.43 ≈ -1.30

Thus, the final results are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Current Ratio": "3.66",
    "Quick Ratio": "2.74",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.20",
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.25",
    "Cash Flow to Debt Ratio": "-1.30"
  }
}
